column3: Subspecies nimia, with range "Aleutian Islands", is considered to be a junior synonym of nominate crecca (Gibson and Kessel 1997, Sangster et al. 2001, Gibson and Byrd 2007), and is deleted. Revise the range description for nominate crecca from "Palearctic region; winters to Africa, India and SE Asia" to "breeds in Palearctic (Iceland south to France, east to eastern Siberia) and the Aleutian Islands; winters from southern and central Europe east to Japan, south to Africa (south to Senegambia, Central African Republic, and Kenya), south Asia, and southeast Asia". The group Green-winged Teal (Eurasian) becomes monotypic; change the scientific name from Anas crecca crecca/nimia to Anas crecca crecca.

column3: Previously we recognized two groups in Amazilia Hummingbird, a polytypic group Amazilia Hummingbird (Amazilia) Amazilia amazilia [amazilia Group], including subspecies azuay, dumerilii, leucophoea, amazilia, and caeruleigularis; and a monotypic Amazilia Hummingbird (Loja) Amazilia amazilia alticola. We no longer recognize the group Amazilia Hummingbird (Loja) Amazilia amazilia alticola. At the same time, we now recognize two new monotypic groups, Amazilia Hummingbird (Green-throated) Amazilia amazilia amazilia and Amazilia Hummingbird (Blue-throated) Amazilia amazilia caeruleigularis. The remaining taxa - azuay, alticola, dumerilii and leucophoea - are combined into the polytypic group Amazilia Hummingbird (White-throated) Amazilia amazilia [dumerilii Group].

column3: In accord with AOS-NACC (Chesser et al. 2019), Blue-vented Hummingbird Amazilia hoffmanni is split from Steely-vented Hummingbird Amazilia saucerottei. Blue-vented Hummingbird is separated from Steely-vented Hummingbird based on differences in vocalizations and behavior (Stiles and Skutch 1989) and on phylogenetic analyses of nuclear and mitochondrial DNA sequences that indicate that Steely-vented Hummingbird as previously constituted was a polyphyletic species (McGuire et al. 2014, Jiménez and Ornelas 2016).

column3: Fischer et al. (2018) described a new taxon of diving-petrel from New Zealand, with range "breeds New Zealand (Codfish Island, off the southern end of the South Island; formerly also bred on the Auckland Islands); range at sea not documented". They described this population as a species, Pelecanoides whenuahouensis, but provisionally we classify it as a subspecies of South Georgia Diving-Petrel, Pelecanoides georgicus whenuahouensis. Because South Georgia Diving-Petrel previously was monotypic, we also add an entry for the nominate subspecies. Revise the range description for nominate georgicus from "Subantarctic circumpolar regions" to "breeds in subantarctic circumpolar regions: South Georgia Island in the southern Atlantic Ocean; Prince Edward, Marion, Crozet, Kerguelen, and Heard Islands in the southern Indian Ocean; and on Macquarie Island, south of New Zealand.
